      <pb n="1"/>
      <p>
        <add>Hebrew</add>
      </p>
      <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>, Friday, Parasha Behar (May)<lb/>
        <date>1854</date>.</p>
      <p>To my beloved friend etc <addressee>Yitzchok Isaac Leeser</addressee>,</p>
      <p>Sir and Dear Friend,</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">Your delightful letter reached me and<lb/> from the depths of my heart I
        express my thanks<lb/> for your affection. It is true I have wherewith<lb/> to support my
        family and I thank God for this<lb/> kindness but the real reason that I wrote to<lb/> you
        is that I saw in your book* that over<lb/> there they are willing to pay $3500 as a
        per–<lb/>manent salary. The canto urged me to write to<lb/> them but before writing I
        thought I ought to<lb/> write to you. For if I remain here all the days of my<lb/> life, I
        could not support my family in my old<lb/> age, and what will I eat on the 7<hi rend="sup"
          >th</hi> year*? That<lb/> is the reason why it occurred to me to leave here.<lb/> Since
        you my friend have decided in your great wis–<lb/>dom that this ought not to be done, I
        shall re–<lb/>frain, and the good God will support me in<lb/> my old age just as in his
        great kindness<lb/> he supports all the creatures who look to his aid.<lb/> Your eternal friend,<lb/>
        <persName role="author">Simon Cohen Noot</persName><lb/>
      </p>
      <p>*probably the Occident *a reference to the year of<lb/> Shemitah, when no work could be
        done<lb/> and one laid on one's savings</p>
    </body>
